commit 715baf7e6351111f5be9aea5ce35d9b537e25dab
Author: Alexander Gordeev <agordeev@linux.ibm.com>

s390/mm: Batch PTE updates in lazy MMU mode

This commit introduces a per-CPU cache to batch PTE updates while in
lazy MMU mode on s390. It aims to reduce the number of IPTE instructions
by applying the cached values with a single multi-IPTE instruction when
leaving the lazy MMU mode.

diff --git a/arch/s390/include/asm/pgtable.h b/arch/s390/include/asm/pgtable.h
--- a/arch/s390/include/asm/pgtable.h
+++ b/arch/s390/include/asm/pgtable.h
[ ... ]
> @@ -1149,6 +1246,26 @@ static __always_inline void __ptep_ipte_range(unsigned long address, int nr,
>  	} while (nr != 255);
>  }
>  
> +#ifdef CONFIG_IPTE_BATCH
> +void arch_enter_lazy_mmu_mode_pte(struct mm_struct *mm,
> +				  unsigned long addr, unsigned long end,
> +				  pte_t *pte);
> +#define arch_enter_lazy_mmu_mode_pte arch_enter_lazy_mmu_mode_pte
> +
> +void arch_pause_lazy_mmu_mode(void);
> +#define arch_pause_lazy_mmu_mode arch_pause_lazy_mmu_mode
> +
> +void arch_resume_lazy_mmu_mode(void);
> +#define arch_resume_lazy_mmu_mode arch_resume_lazy_mmu_mode

Are these pause and resume functions defined anywhere in this patch? 

It looks like declaring the macros suppresses the generic weak fallback 
implementations, but without the actual definitions in the architecture 
code, won't this cause undefined reference errors during linking?

[ ... ]
> +static inline pte_t ptep_get_and_clear(struct mm_struct *mm,
> +				       unsigned long addr, pte_t *ptep)
> +{
> +	pte_t res;
> +
> +	if (!ipte_batch_ptep_get_and_clear(mm, addr, ptep, &res))
> +		res = __ptep_get_and_clear(mm, addr, ptep);
> +	page_table_check_pte_clear(mm, addr, res);
> +	return res;
> +}

If the batching function returns true, the original __ptep_get_and_clear() 
and __ptep_get_and_clear_full() are bypassed. Does this skip the mandatory 
tear down of secure memory for the Ultravisor?

The original functions call uv_convert_from_secure_pte() and 
uv_destroy_pte() when mm_is_protected(mm) is true. If these are bypassed, 
won't protected VM pages be freed without notifying the Ultravisor, leading 
to hardware checkstops when the host reallocates them?

[ ... ]
> +static inline void ptep_set_wrprotect(struct mm_struct *mm,
> +				      unsigned long addr, pte_t *ptep)
> +{
> +	if (!ipte_batch_ptep_set_wrprotect(mm, addr, ptep))
> +		__ptep_set_wrprotect(mm, addr, ptep);
> +}

Since the actual hardware PTE updates and TLB flushes are delayed until 
arch_leave_lazy_mmu_mode(), does this create a race window during operations 
like fork() and mprotect()?

For example, during fork(), copy_pte_range() write-protects the parent's 
PTEs to enforce Copy-On-Write. If the hardware PTE remains writable until 
the batch commits, couldn't concurrent threads in the parent write to the 
page without faulting, causing the child to observe these writes and 
breaking COW semantics?

Similarly, during mprotect(), could concurrent lockless page table walkers 
like gup_fast() read the stale, permissive hardware PTEs to acquire invalid 
write pins on memory that is being marked read-only?

diff --git a/arch/s390/mm/ipte_batch.c b/arch/s390/mm/ipte_batch.c
--- /dev/null
+++ b/arch/s390/mm/ipte_batch.c
> @@ -0,0 +1,396 @@
> +// SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0
> +#include <linux/pgtable.h>
> +#include <asm/facility.h>
> +#include <kunit/visibility.h>
> +
> +#define PTE_POISON	0

Is 0 safe to use as a magic value to identify untouched entries?

On s390, a PTE value of 0 is a valid, fully permissive mapping of physical 
address 0. If a legitimate kernel operation updates a PTE to 0, wouldn't 
leave_ipte_batch() see it as PTE_POISON and skip the entry, leaving a stale 
and potentially permissive PTE active in the hardware page table?

[ ... ]
> +static void leave_ipte_batch(void)
> +{
> +	pte_t *ptep, *start, *start_cache, *cache;
> +	unsigned long start_addr, addr;
> +	struct ipte_batch *ib;
> +	int start_idx;
[ ... ]
> +	for (ptep = start; ptep < ib->end_pte; ptep++, cache++, addr += PAGE_SIZE) {
> +		if (pte_val(*cache) == PTE_POISON) {
> +			if (start) {
> +				set_pte_range(ib->mm, start_addr, start, ptep, start_cache);
> +				start = NULL;
> +			}
> +		} else if (!start) {
> +			start = ptep;
> +			start_addr = addr;
> +			start_cache = cache;
> +		}
> +	}
> +	set_pte_range(ib->mm, start_addr, start, ptep, start_cache);

Can this result in a NULL pointer dereference?

If the very last element in the batched range evaluates to PTE_POISON, the 
loop will finish with start == NULL. The subsequent call to set_pte_range() 
passes this NULL pointer.

set_pte_range() then calls:
    nr_ptes = invalidate_pte_range(mm, addr, ptep, end);

Which in turn calls:
    nr_ptes = count_contiguous(start, end, &valid);

Inside count_contiguous(), the code does:
    *valid = !(pte_val(*start) & _PAGE_INVALID);

Which will unconditionally dereference the NULL start pointer.

[ ... ]
> +bool ipte_batch_ptep_get_and_clear_full(struct mm_struct *mm,
> +					unsigned long addr, pte_t *ptep,
> +					int full, pte_t *res)
> +{
> +	struct ipte_batch *ib;
> +	pte_t pte, old;
> +
> +	ib = get_ipte_batch(mm, ptep);
> +	if (!ib)
> +		return false;
> +
> +	old = __ipte_batch_ptep_get(ib, ptep);
> +	pte = __pte(_PAGE_INVALID);
> +	__ipte_batch_set_pte(ib, ptep, pte);

Does this batching logic drop the optimizations from the original PTE 
operations?

In the original __ptep_get_and_clear_full(), the full parameter prevents the 
expensive IPTE instruction during address space teardown, relying on a later 
bulk flush. Here, it seems the full parameter is ignored and the clear is 
queued anyway.

[ ... ]
> +bool ipte_batch_ptep_set_wrprotect(struct mm_struct *mm,
> +				   unsigned long addr, pte_t *ptep)
> +{
> +	struct ipte_batch *ib;
> +	pte_t pte, old;
> +
> +	ib = get_ipte_batch(mm, ptep);
> +	if (!ib)
> +		return false;
> +
> +	old = __ipte_batch_ptep_get(ib, ptep);
> +	pte = pte_wrprotect(old);
> +	__ipte_batch_set_pte(ib, ptep, pte);

The original __ptep_set_wrprotect() checks if (pte_write(pte)) before 
modifying. Since this batching unconditionally caches the write-protected 
PTE, won't it cause leave_ipte_batch() to issue IPTE TLB flushes even for 
pages that were already read-only?

